      <format>text/x-wiki</format>
      <text bytes="22438" xml:space="preserve">{{short description|Ratio of the desired signal to the background noise}}
{{redirect|Signal-to-noise|statistics|Effect size|other uses|}}
'''Signal-to-noise ratio''' ('''SNR''' or '''S/N''') is a measure used in [[science and engineering]] that compares the level of a desired [[signal (electrical engineering)|signal]] to the level of background [[Noise (signal processing)|noise]]. SNR is defined as the ratio of signal power to the [[noise power]], often expressed in [[decibel]]s. A ratio higher than 1:1 (greater than 0&amp;nbsp;dB) indicates more signal than noise.

SNR, [[bandwidth (signal processing)|bandwidth]], and [[channel capacity]] of a [[communication channel]] are connected by the [[Shannon–Hartley theorem]].

==Definition==
Signal-to-noise ratio is defined as the ratio of the [[power (physics)|power]] of a [[signal (information theory)|signal]] (meaningful input) to the power of background [[noise (electronic)|noise]] (meaningless or unwanted input):
:&lt;math&gt;
\mathrm{SNR} = \frac{P_\mathrm{signal}}{P_\mathrm{noise}},
&lt;/math&gt;
where {{mvar|P}} is average power. Both signal and noise power must be measured at the same or equivalent points in a system, and within the same system [[bandwidth (signal processing)|bandwidth]].

Depending on whether the signal is a constant ({{mvar|s}}) or a random variable ({{mvar|S}}), the signal-to-noise ratio for random noise {{mvar|N}} becomes:&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book |authors=Charles Sherman and John Butler |title=Transducers and Arrays for Underwater Sound |date=2007 |publisher=Springer Science &amp; Business Media |isbn=9780387331393 |page=276 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=srREi-ScbFcC&amp;q=%22signal+to+noise+ratio%22+define+mean-square&amp;pg=PA276}}&lt;/ref&gt;
:&lt;math&gt;
\mathrm{SNR} = \frac{s^2}{\mathrm{E}[N^2]}
&lt;/math&gt;
where E refers to the [[expected value]], i.e. in this case the [[mean square]] of {{mvar|N}},
or
:&lt;math&gt;
\mathrm{SNR} = \frac{\mathrm{E}[S^2]}{\mathrm{E}[N^2]}
&lt;/math&gt;

If the noise has [[expected value]] of zero, as is common, the denominator is its [[variance]], the square of its [[standard deviation]] {{math|''σ''&lt;sub&gt;N&lt;/sub&gt;}}.


The signal and the noise must be measured the same way, for example as voltages across the same [[Electrical impedance|impedance]].  The [[root mean square]]s can alternatively be used in the ratio:
:&lt;math&gt;
\mathrm{SNR} = \frac{P_\mathrm{signal}}{P_\mathrm{noise}} = \left ( \frac{A_\mathrm{signal}}{A_\mathrm{noise} } \right )^2,
&lt;/math&gt;
where {{mvar|A}} is [[root mean square (RMS) amplitude]] (for example, RMS voltage).

===Decibels===
Because many signals have a very wide [[dynamic range]], signals are often expressed using the [[logarithm]]ic [[decibel]] scale. Based upon the definition of decibel, signal and noise may be expressed in decibels (dB) as

:&lt;math&gt;P_\mathrm{signal,dB} = 10 \log_{10} \left ( P_\mathrm{signal} \right ) &lt;/math&gt;

and

:&lt;math&gt;P_\mathrm{noise,dB} = 10 \log_{10} \left ( P_\mathrm{noise} \right ). &lt;/math&gt;

In a similar manner, SNR may be expressed in decibels as

:&lt;math&gt;
\mathrm{SNR_{dB}} = 10 \log_{10} \left ( \mathrm{SNR} \right ).
&lt;/math&gt;

Using the definition of SNR
